At this point, I think it makes sense to tackle the fundamental TODOs mentioned above and then explore further precompilation in follow-up PRs. Are there any people interested in testing macOS (M1/x64?) or Windows (edit: I've started a Windows run)? It could be as simple as checking out this PR and then running
```sh
lake clean && time lake build
git checkout 04155008c1bd958624d2184e1bd1f5a1cbdff452  # PR base commit
lake clean && time lake build
```

@Kha A potential style suggestion: You can set `moreLeanArgs` on the `package` to set arguments on all the package's targets e.g.,

```lean
package mathlib where
  moreLeanArgs := #[
    "-DwarningAsError=true",
    "-Dpp.unicode.fun=true" -- pretty-prints `fun a  b`
  ]
```

Windows is not too happy yet: precompilation increases total build time from 29m12s to 29m47s. This might be, as pointed out before, because of the naive `dlsym` emulation in the interpreter that loops over all modules loaded into the process, i.e. scales linearly with the number of `--load-dynlib`s.

I tried benchmarking this (intel macos), but did two runs of this PR and got wildly different results (from `lake clean && time lake build` both times):
```
lake build  21737.87s user 1546.88s system 1204% cpu 32:12.56 total
lake build  16027.82s user 1224.07s system 1275% cpu 22:32.53 total
```
Not sure what to make of that. :-(

Benchmarking the base commit gives:
```
lake build  16414.45s user 1447.86s system 1239% cpu 24:00.93 total
lake build  17871.27s user 1564.50s system 1215% cpu 26:38.44 total
```
In light of #3632, I have removed the `ToAdditive` changes, leaving only the zero-dependencies `Rename` precompilation

@tydeu In order to keep the .olean traces platform-independent, we would have to stop including the contents of precompilation .o and .so files in the trace. This seems like a strict improvement, there is no conceivable scenario to me where hashing them would prevent rebuilds compared to hashing only the much smaller .c input files.

@Kha 

>  This seems like a strict improvement, there is no conceivable scenario to me where hashing them would prevent rebuilds compared to hashing only the much smaller .c input files.

I am not sure about this. For one, in my experience, while native shared libraries (e.g. `so`) are bigger, the `.o` files are generally smaller than the `.c` files. Second, `.o` files are created after optimization, and native libraries after linking, so either step can either simplify things (e.g., inlining. eliminating dead code, etc.) code which can prevent rebuilds. I have definitely observe cases where the `.o` file is rebuilt but relinking is unnecessary. Furthermore, we rebuild the `.o` based on C compiler flags and the native libraries based on linker flags, which may be platform-specific and do need to be part of the trace.

Regardless, if we do want to do this, it should not be difficult. This would simply require the resulting trace of the `.o` file to be its input trace (e.g., the `.c` file and its C flags) -- likely in `buildLeanO`.

> the `.o` files are generally smaller than the `.c` files

Ah, this indeed can be true for Lean's pre-optimized .c files. Though hashing only .c is of course still faster than .c + .o + .so.



> I have definitely observe cases where the `.o` file is rebuilt but relinking is unnecessary

I didn't expect that, but fortunately linking is the fastest step anyway.



> Furthermore, we rebuild the `.o` based on C compiler flags and the native libraries based on linker flags

Fortunately this should not be an issue for precompilation of pure-Lean projects like mathlib.

In any case, I would also be happy with making the native code hashing an opt-out.
@tydeu This seems to work fine out of the box, but are there any guarantees about what happens when a module is included in multiple `lean_lib`s? Do the last lib's settings win?

@Kha I do not think so? It currently searches an `Array` constructed from a `fold` of a `RBMap`, so the order is largely up in the air (though maybe the sorted order of tree enables this use case?). This could be solved definitively in the future with some form of `OrdRBMap` that preserves ordering to retain the ordering of the definitions in the file.
For future reference, a strict order of libraries has been established and the last one now wins: leanprover/lean4#2937.

At this point, I think it makes sense to tackle the fundamental TODOs mentioned above and then explore further precompilation in follow-up PRs. Are there any people interested in testing macOS (M1/x64?) or Windows (edit: I've started a Windows run)? It could be as simple as checking out this PR and then running
```sh
lake clean && time lake build
git checkout 04155008c1bd958624d2184e1bd1f5a1cbdff452  # PR base commit
lake clean && time lake build
```

@Kha A potential style suggestion: You can set `moreLeanArgs` on the `package` to set arguments on all the package's targets e.g.,

```lean
package mathlib where
  moreLeanArgs := #[
    "-DwarningAsError=true",
    "-Dpp.unicode.fun=true" -- pretty-prints `fun a  b`
  ]
```

Windows is not too happy yet: precompilation increases total build time from 29m12s to 29m47s. This might be, as pointed out before, because of the naive `dlsym` emulation in the interpreter that loops over all modules loaded into the process, i.e. scales linearly with the number of `--load-dynlib`s.
!bench

In light of #3632, I have removed the `ToAdditive` changes, leaving only the zero-dependencies `Rename` precompilation

@tydeu In order to keep the .olean traces platform-independent, we would have to stop including the contents of precompilation .o and .so files in the trace. This seems like a strict improvement, there is no conceivable scenario to me where hashing them would prevent rebuilds compared to hashing only the much smaller .c input files.

@Kha 

>  This seems like a strict improvement, there is no conceivable scenario to me where hashing them would prevent rebuilds compared to hashing only the much smaller .c input files.

I am not sure about this. For one, in my experience, while native shared libraries (e.g. `so`) are bigger, the `.o` files are generally smaller than the `.c` files. Second, `.o` files are created after optimization, and native libraries after linking, so either step can either simplify things (e.g., inlining. eliminating dead code, etc.) code which can prevent rebuilds. I have definitely observe cases where the `.o` file is rebuilt but relinking is unnecessary. Furthermore, we rebuild the `.o` based on C compiler flags and the native libraries based on linker flags, which may be platform-specific and do need to be part of the trace.

Regardless, if we do want to do this, it should not be difficult. This would simply require the resulting trace of the `.o` file to be its input trace (e.g., the `.c` file and its C flags) -- likely in `buildLeanO`.

> the `.o` files are generally smaller than the `.c` files

Ah, this indeed can be true for Lean's pre-optimized .c files. Though hashing only .c is of course still faster than .c + .o + .so.



> I have definitely observe cases where the `.o` file is rebuilt but relinking is unnecessary

I didn't expect that, but fortunately linking is the fastest step anyway.



> Furthermore, we rebuild the `.o` based on C compiler flags and the native libraries based on linker flags

Fortunately this should not be an issue for precompilation of pure-Lean projects like mathlib.

In any case, I would also be happy with making the native code hashing an opt-out.
